natural problem: If $\sqrt{5 + x} + \sqrt{20 - x} = 7$, what is the value of $(5 + x)(20 - x)$?
natural solution: Square both sides of the equation to obtain \[ (5+x)+2\sqrt{5+x}\sqrt{20-x}+(20-x)=49. \]This equation simplifies to \[ 2\sqrt{(5+x)(20-x)}=24, \]so $(5+x)(20-x)=(24/2)^2=\boxed{144}$.
